  res.json(sanitizedUsers);
});
```

---

### 🟠 MEDIUM — No Global Error Handler (OWASP A09:2021 – Security Logging & Monitoring)

If any middleware or route throws, Express's default error handler sends a stack trace in development mode, leaking internal paths and dependency versions.

**Recommendation:**
```js
// Place AFTER all routes
app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  console.error(`[${new Date().toISOString()}] Error: ${err.message}`);
  res.status(500).json({ error: 'Internal server error' });
});
```

---

### 🟡 LOW — Hardcoded Port with No Environment Variable

Port 3000 is hardcoded. In production, this should come from an environment variable.

```js
const PORT = process.env.PORT || 3000;
app.listen(PORT, () => {
  console.log(`Server running on port ${PORT}`);
});
```

---

### 🟡 LOW — No Request Logging / Audit Trail

No logging middleware means zero visibility into who accesses what. Security incidents become undetectable.

```js
const morgan = require('morgan');
app.use(morgan('combined'));  // Apache-style access logs
```

---

### 🟡 LOW — Express Version Fingerprinting

By default, Express sends `X-Powered-By: Express`, revealing the framework to attackers. `helmet()` removes this, but it can also be done standalone:

```js
app.disable('x-powered-by');
```

